[1
Date: 5 Sep 2001 12:13:25 +0900
From: Akira Goto <m1774@geocities.co.jp>
Source: English Joong-Ang Ilbo, 30 Aug 2001 [edited
<http://www.hankooki.com/times/200108/t2001083017301440110.htm>

Cholera Has Surfaced in Ulsan
-----------------------------
The [South Korean National Institute of Health (NIH) yesterday reported an
outbreak of cholera in the southeastern city of Ulsan, South Kyongsang
Province. This is the first such occurrence since 1999, when 3 patients
were diagnosed with cholera in South Cholla Province. A patient in his 60s
showed symptoms of diarrhea after eating raw fish, but a medical diagnosis
revealed that he had contracted the disease, NIH said.
As part of efforts to see if there are another patients infected by cholera
and to prevent the spread of the disease, the NIH is conducting
investigations across the region with the cooperation of a group of
epidemic specialists from medical organizations, NIH officials stated. To
prevent the disease, people should boil their drinking water and eat
well-cooked food, as well as refrain from eating raw fish, according to the
NIH officials.
******
[2
Date: 6 Sep 2001
Source: English Joong-Ang Ilbo 3 Sep 2001 [edited
<http://www.hankooki.com/times/200109/t2001090317085240110.htm>

Concern Mounts as Cholera Spreads in Kyongsang Region
-----------------------------------------------------
Shortly after this year's first case of cholera was discovered in the
southeastern city of Ulsan, 7 more people were found to have contracted the
disease in Yongchon, North Kyongsang Province, the [South Korean National
Institute of Health (NIH) reported yesterday. They all had diarrhea and
stomach pains after dining at a restaurant in Yongchon, some 300 km
southeast of Seoul, the NIH said.
It also reported that more than 100 other people ate at the same restaurant
around the day that the 7 patients did. The medical authorities isolated
all of them in a bid to carry out emergency check-ups and prevent a further
spread of the disease, and did not rule out the possibility that the region
could see more cholera patients and that the sickness could spread to the
surrounding areas. Earlier, the NIH warned of a large-scale outbreak of
cholera this year, which usually surfaces every 10 years. The nation had
more than 100 cholera patients in 1980 and 1991.
To prevent the disease, people are advised to boil their drinking water and
eat well-cooked food, as well as refrain from eating raw fish, according to
the NIH officials.
[Byline: Na Jeong-ju
